<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
The important number is not max dmg, its avg dmg.  I cant prove it now, but the accepted formula of many post Ive seen is this (rating * 2 + hard bonus).  This magic number has been prove over many pages of log, and is only an estimation of what the avg number really is.<P>The thing to note is the 2 type of dmg you can do.<P>There is the linear dmg, proportional to your weapon rating, your skill and your str.<P>Linear dmg is easy to take into account since its linear. (What an explanation).<P>For example, if you compare a dmg 20 weapon vs a dmg 10.  A lvl 50 warrior with 150 str get a 50 str bonus.  Max dmg for 20 dmg weapon is 88 given the above formula.  With 50 more str, the max dmg will be 90 + 8 = 98. Max dmg on the 10dgm weapon will be 45 + 8 = 53 instead of 48.  Increase of 10 for 20dmg weapon, 5 for 10 dmg weapon, pretty linear.  So in theory, if you raise only your str, if you hit, you may do more dmg, but thats also the case for the faster weapon, thus maintaining the comparaison.<P>The important factor is avg dmg, but more importantly is the hard bonus.  This bonus is 8 at lvl 50.  Like I explained earlier, if you have 20 attack with the 10dmg weapon, and hit 10 times, you get 10 * 8 = 80 from the hard non linear bonus.  With the 20 dmg weapon, lets say you atk 10 times, hit 5 times, you do same linear dmg, but your bonus dmg is 40.  So, vs 2 weapon with same ratio, the faster weapon just did 40 more dmg.<P>Each time you either increase your chance to hit, or you increase your atk speed (the other form of dmg I mention earlier), you augment the difference betweem the bonus from the faster weapons vs the slower weapons. If in any given time you manage to land 2 more attack on a foe vs 1 more attack with a slow weapon, all ratio being equal, you just possibly did 8 more dmg.<P>1 thing to note also is that this hard bonus does not always kick in, it probably need to be roll to like any other roll.  But since its all the same roll for all atk, it probably can be ignore.  It would somewhat reduce the difference between 1-h vs 2-h in the favor of 2-h, but would not change the differences.<P>Hope it shed a bit more light.<P>Thorbadin
